ATLaura::Friday, February 26, 2016 6:42 AM::<comment>I think the author could have done a little more background on Booker and its effects on sentencing before writing an entire article about one district court judge's beef with the sentencing guidelines.  Perhaps look at the ten years of sentencing statistics post Booker to see how district court judges sentence and how appellate courts review those sentences, which I'm pretty sure the Sentencing Commission keeps.  Booker was a sea change.  I think the statistics would show that sentencing reform advocates need to focus their attention elsewhere now that the guidelines are merely advisory.  Mandatory minimums coupled with prosecutorial charging discretion has had a lot more to do with filling our federal prisons than the sentencing guidelines, which even now play a valuable role (albeit a much smaller one) in making sure judges' sentences don't become subject to mere whims and arbitrariness.</comment>

Matthew Van Meter::Friday, February 26, 2016 11:25 AM::<comment>Hi, thanks for all your astute comments. Part of what got me initially interested in this topic is that the situation post-Booker is unsettled. As you point out, the mandatory minimums are far more influential now; the Guidelines are past. That's totally what I thought when I started reporting this piece.... But, according to the US Sentencing Commission (whose data I do not take completely at face value, but they're the best we have) most judges have NOT deviated significantly from the Guidelines post-Booker. And our federal prison population continues to grow faster than before, even if you control for people sentenced under mandatory minimums. There are all kinds of theories about why, but for some reason the Guidelines seem as prevalent as ever.</comment>

ATLaura::Tuesday, March 1, 2016 8:39 AM::<comment>Hi Matthew, if I look at the Sentencing Commission's 2014 statistics from their website, 46% of defendants were sentenced within the guideline range, while just shy of 52% were sentenced BELOW the guideline range, either as a result of a departure or a variance, or both.  Surprisingly, only 2.2% of defendants received a sentence above the guideline range, so there does not appear to be a tendency for "hanging judges" to impose harsher sentences, as another commenter suggested.  Not sure where you're getting your data from, but the Commission's 2014 statistics suggest judges are willing to go below the guideline range when they think it's appropriate to do so.</comment>

Matthew Van Meter::Wednesday, March 2, 2016 3:41 AM::<comment>Hey, yeah that's totally what I thought when I started reporting this piece. Forty-six percent seems really low, right? Now, you may well know more about this than I do, but here's how I ended up conceptualizing the issue: First, it's instructive to dig in a bit to the Sentencing Commission's archive, especially the 2005 Annual Report (linked below), which captures Guidelines application immediately pre- and post-Booker. Guidelines compliance pre-Booker was about 70%, post-Booker was about 61%. Then I wondered where that 9% change came from. Did it come from all judges exercising roughly 9% more discretion, or what? It turns out that, if you look at the reports by district for that year, the change was concentrated almost completely in a few jurisdictions (especially small jurisdictions, like Vermont and Idaho). I suspect (and I can only suspect--the USSC refused to give me judge-by-judge data, although they have it) that, even within those jurisdictions, the change was concentrated in a few judges who, like Coughenour, were just waiting for the opportunity to flout the Guidelines. Each year, the national compliance figure has declined, but that change has continued to be concentrated in a few judges: most judges are very compliant (around 70% within guidelines, like before Booker). A small but growing number are spectacularly non-compliant. I hinted at this a bit in my paragraph about whether these discrepancies are in fact evidence of the very discretion Coughenour wants. So you're right that compliance was 46% in FY 2014, but I think the granular information tells a subtle story about why that is. I may have overstated that case in my above comment, though, so you were right to take issue with my description. The Guidelines have definitely decreased in importance over time. Just not as much as it seems on first glance.As for upward departures, those have always been exceedingly rare. I suspect they are rare because (and here's perhaps where I show my ideological hand) the Guidelines ranges are SO high already that it would take a very harsh judge indeed to depart up.http://www.ussc.gov/sites/defa...</comment>

Matthew Van Meter::Wednesday, March 2, 2016 3:48 AM::<comment>Another thing that bears mentioning is that judges are still required to calculate the Guidelines on the record and use them as a baseline, which imparts a subtle upward pressure on sentences. Sentences have not precipitously declined since Booker.The Guidelines are also used as the standard of appellate review. When the 9th Circuit overturned Coughenour's second sentencing of Ressam (which was post-Booker), it was for an "abuse of discretion" because his sentence was so far below the prescribed range, and the Guidelines are still presumptively fair.</comment>

Tom_Tildrum::Friday, February 26, 2016 8:07 AM::<comment>Discretion is a two-way street. For every Coughenor who wants to impose lighter sentences, there's going to be a hanging judge who wants to be harsher. It would be interesting to pin Van Meter down as to whether his real goal is discretion or just leniency.</comment>

Matthew Van Meter::Saturday, February 27, 2016 12:31 AM::<comment>Hi Tom. Thanks for the comment. When you said "his real goal," did you mean my goal or Coughenour's?If the former, I don't really have a goal. I don't pretend to be unbiased (I'm pretty defense-minded), but I was drawn to this issue because I'm fascinated by the questions raised by this issue, questions that are fundamental to how we administer justice: Who decides what an appropriate sentence is? What is the goal of a prison sentence? Whom do we trust to make those determinations?If the latter, I think Coughenour takes his role as sentencer very seriously. He agonizes over every decision, and he is not always on the side of "leniency." If his sentences sometimes seem lenient, I think he'd say that it's because the baseline sentences have become so absurdly long under the Guidelines.Hope that answers your question.</comment>

